\sec Attempt to understand the proof of Cherbonnier-Colmez theorem

After this kind of {\it summary} of the proof should follow a detailed proof.
\secc Tate Sen Condition

First we show that the relevant quadruple satisfies Tate Sen's conditions.

What is the quadruple? It is
$(\mytilde\Lambda,v,G_0,\Lambda_{H_{L,n}})$. Here
$$\mytilde\Lambda=\mytilde{\ao1}, v=\vo1, G_0=G_{K_0},\Lambda_{H_{L,n}}=\varphi^{-n}(\ao1).$$

\begitems
*  Now to verify the first condition, take finite extensions
$L\supseteq M\supseteq K_0$. Let $\alpha=[\bar\pi_L](\sum_{\tau\in H_M/H_L}\tau([\bar\pi_L]))^{-1}$.

Then $$\sum_{\tau\in H_M/H_L}\tau(\varphi^{-n}(\alpha))=1,\,\forall n.$$
(Note: just expand it)
Moreover, $$\limits\lim{n\rightarrow\infty}\vo1(\varphi^{-n}(\alpha))=0.$$

So we can take the desired $\alpha$ as $\varphi^{-n}(\alpha)$ for sufficiently large $n$;
This proves the quadruple satisfies the first condition.
*  Then for the second condition, take $n$ so large that $p^nr_L\geq1$.

Define $\rl n$ by use of the following commutative diagram:

\bpi
\node(rln) {$\rl n:$};
\node(tao) [right=of rln] {$\tao1_L$};
\node(aon) [right=of tao] {$\ao1_{L,n}$};
\node(aonk) [below=of tao] {$\ao1_{L,n+k}$};
\draw[-latex,thick] (tao) -- (aon);
\draw[right hook-latex,thick] (aonk) -- (tao);
\draw[-latex,thick] (aonk) to node [auto,swap] {$\scriptstyle\varphi^{-n}\circ\psi^k\circ\varphi^{n+k}$} (aon);
\epi

So what is this $\psi$?       % check the paper!

Since $\psi\circ\varphi=\id$, we find that
$\varphi^{-n}\circ\psi^k\circ\varphi^{n+k}$ does not depend on $k$, so, by definiton,
for $x\in\limits\bigcup{k\geq0}\ao1_{L,n+k}$, we observe that

\begitems\style a
* $\rl n\circ\rl{n+m}=\rl n$.
* If $x\in\ao1_{L,n}$, then $\rl n(x)=x$.
* $\rl n$ is $\ao1_{L,n+k}$-linear.
* $\limits\lim{n\rightarrow\infty}\rl n(x)=x$.
\enditems

Moreover, for $x=\varphi^{-n-k}(y)\in\ao1_{L,n+k}$, we have
$$\rl n(x)=\varphi^{-n}(\psi^k(y))=\varphi^{-n-k}(\varphi^k\psi^k(y)).$$ Then write
$y=\sum_{i=0}^{p-k-1}[\varepsilon]^i\varphi^k(y_i)$. By corollary 4.30, we know $\psi^k(y)=y_0$,
thus $$\vo1(\rl n(x))=\vo1(\varphi^{-n}(y_0))\geq\vo1(\varphi^{-n-k}(y))=\vo1(x).$$
%% where does the inequality come from?
%% We move the rest of the proof to the section of detialed proofs.

\enditems

\secc Sketch.

Basically we prove these conditions in order to do an {\basebf almost étale descent},
i.e. find an $M\in\gl_d(\mytilde\Lambda)$ such that the {\bf conjugated} cocycle lies
in $\gl_d(\ao1_{K,n})$ and is trivial on $H'_K$.

Now a representation gives rise to a continuous cocycle viâ taking the basis
representation of an element in $G_K$.

Moreover, we can find a matrix $N\in\gl_d(A)$ such that the conjugated cocycle by $N$
is trivial on $H'_K$. Now apply lemma 3.45. to obtain that when $n$ is large enough,
then $C\in\gl_d(\ao1_{K,n})$.

The last part is a little bit mysterious, as I am not very sure how the process of
translating into representations goes, but I guess this is like the opposite of
taking the basis we did above.

In fact, if I guessed it right, then this is like the module obtained from the basis,
when tensored with the original representation, becomes the trivial representation.

Writing this out, I would imagine, then immediately gives the long-desired result.

\sec Details

This is the detailed proof of the theorem in question!

